website/README.md
     3â†’## Getting Started
     5â†’First, run the development server:
     6â†’
     7â†’```bash
     8â†’npm run dev
     9â†’# or
    10â†’yarn dev
    11â†’# or
    12â†’pnpm dev
    13â†’```
    14â†’
    15â†’Open [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000) with your browser to see the result.
    16â†’
    17â†’You can start editing the page by modifying `app/page.tsx`. The page auto-updates as you edit the file.
    18â†’
    19â†’[API routes](https://nextjs.org/docs/api-routes/introduction) can be accessed on [http://localhost:3000/api/hello](http://localhost:3000/api/hello). This endpoint can be edited in `pages/api/hello.ts`.
    20â†’
    21â†’The `pages/api` directory is mapped to `/api/*`. Files in this directory are treated as [API routes](https://nextjs.org/docs/api-routes/introduction) instead of React pages.
    22â†’
    23â†’This project uses [`next/font`](https://nextjs.org/docs/basic-features/font-optimization) to automatically optimize and load Inter, a custom Google Font.
    24â†’
    25â†’## Learn More
    27â†’To learn more about Next.js, take a look at the following resources:
    28â†’
    29â†’- [Next.js Documentation](https://nextjs.org/docs) - learn about Next.js features and API.
    30â†’- [Learn Next.js](https://nextjs.org/learn) - an interactive Next.js tutorial.
    31â†’
    32â†’You can check out [the Next.js GitHub repository](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/) - your feedback and contributions are welcome!
    33â†’
    34â†’## Deploy on Vercel
    36â†’The easiest way to deploy your Next.js app is to use the [Vercel Platform](https://vercel.com/new?utm_medium=default-template&filter=next.js&utm_source=create-next-app&utm_campaign=create-next-app-readme) from the creators of Next.js.
    37â†’
    38â†’Check out our [Next.js deployment documentation](https://nextjs.org/docs/deployment) for more details.
